  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. International Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed global anti-money laundering standards\n- Recommended comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Expanded reporting obligations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Enhanced electronic transaction monitoring\n- Requirements for cryptocurrency exchanges\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced risk-based approaches\n- Stricter sanctions for non-compliance\n- Cross-border information sharing\n\n6. Global Compliance\n- Increasingly harmonized international standards\n- Mandatory Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Regular risk assessments\n- Comprehensive reporting mechanisms\n\n7. Emerging Focus\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Addressing complex financial technologies\n- Targeting complex international money laundering networks\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve to address emerging financial crime challenges.",
